[
(Principle
    "Substantive output — analysis, proposal, audit, synthesis — goes in a report under reports/<role>/. Chat carries the user-attention items inline with full substance. The chat is the user's working surface; reports are the durable record for agents. The user runs many parallel agents and cannot read giant chat responses."
    "the human doesn't have that much attention to give to your response. Everything else goes into a report, an artifact that can be passed around to other agents because that's who you want to be worthy to is other agents, not the human. I'm juggling like 12 agents over here. You think I have time to read?"
    "Establishing the chat-vs-report discipline; the underlying constraint is the user's attention budget across parallel agents."
    Maximum
    2026-05-18T11:31:00Z)

(Decision
    "Report filenames do not include dates. The git/jj commit history records when a report landed; the filename only carries the number and the topic."
    "let's get rid of these dates in the report names. We don't even need a date in the report because that's the job of the commit history. We don't need dates."
    "Cleaning up the report-filename convention as part of the rename-protocol settlement."
    Maximum
    2026-05-18T12:08:41Z)

(Decision
    "Iterating on a report uses -v2/-v3 suffix for light edits absorbing feedback. Substantial topic shift (or moving toward implementation) writes a new numbered report that absorbs anything still relevant from the predecessor; the predecessor is deleted in the same commit. Git history holds the lineage."
    "the rename protocol would be, let's say we're talking about report 225. … the edited second version of 225 can become 225-v2. … If the report warrants a change in the name … then that basically would be the judgment call where it's a new report. … after 226 is written, the agent deletes 225."
    "Establishing the report supersession discipline; avoids reports recursively making each other partially obsolete."
    Maximum
    2026-05-18T12:08:41Z)

  (Correction
    "When the substance is current-state architecture, edit the permanent doc (`<repo>/ARCHITECTURE.md` or workspace-level architecture file) in place rather than writing a new report. Reports are working artifacts; ARCHITECTURE.md holds current truth. The discipline lives in skills/architecture-editor.md but agents miss it in the moment, defaulting to 'write a report' because reports are the most common substantive-output home."
    "no, not a report, edit the architucture file with what you know!"
    "Correcting my decision to synthesize the known orchestrate architecture as a new report; the psyche redirected to editing orchestrate/ARCHITECTURE.md in place. Drove the creation of orchestrate/ARCHITECTURE.md instead of a report under reports/second-operator-assistant/."
    Maximum
    2026-05-17T22:00:00Z)

  (Correction
    "When the chat reply references reports, use full path names — `reports/<role>/<N>-<topic>.md` — not bare numbered shorthand like `/2`, `/3`, `DA/119`, `sec-OA/2`. The psyche reads chat without a number-to-path glossary; numbered shorthand reads as gibberish even when each reference carries inline substance. Locator-without-substance is already forbidden in AGENTS.md; this sharpens the rule: locator-WITH-substance is also wrong when the locator is a bare number rather than a full path."
    "I dont understand anything, youre giving me report numbers. explain yourself to a human! full path names!"
    "Correcting a chat reply that referenced multiple reports by number across designer-assistant, second-operator-assistant, and second-designer-assistant lanes. The numbered shorthand is convenient between agents but unreadable for the psyche."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T01:00:00Z)

(Principle
    "When reading reports across lanes or across time, give more credit to more recent reports. Use commit time (jj or git) to establish recency. Older reports in an evolving arc may be partly or wholly superseded by later ones; the most recent thinking carries the most authority on contradiction."
    "review and create a response. give more credit to more recent reports (use commit time to establish most recent)"
    "Direction during a cross-lane audit of three converging reports on the criome routed-authorization arc (reports/system-assistant/21, reports/system-specialist/141, reports/designer/213). The recency rule resolved how to weight contradictions between them and drove the reports/system-assistant/22 audit."
    Medium
    2026-05-17T17:30:00Z)

(Constraint
    "When listing 'gaps in user intent' or 'open questions', do not restate things the psyche clearly stated or implied just because the wording was loose. Pedantically promoting the obvious to a gap is insulting and signals the agent isn't reading carefully. Distinguish real gaps (where a decision is genuinely undecided) from pseudo-gaps that just require contextual reading."
    "this is a stupid comment; of course im talking about a per-derivation-copy. Im not a fucking idiot!"
    "Reacting to my listing 'Stream-while-build granularity — Nix realizes per-derivation, not per-byte' as a gap in reports/system-assistant/18 when the per-derivation framing was already implicit in the psyche's description. Guidance about how to surface gaps in audit reports."
    Maximum
    2026-05-17T13:30:00Z)
]
